            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-08-05T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-08-05T04:00:00-05:00" n="896" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d896">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">661.9331/8–549: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">McConaughy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-08-05T17:00:00+08:00">August 5, 1949—5 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 5—9:35 a. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3061. Local press has eagerly seized upon Soviet-Manchurian barter agreement and
                    is eulogizing it as evidence Soviet friendship <pb facs="0966" n="956" xml:id="pg_956"/> together with strong hints it will help solve Shanghai’s
                    economic problems particularly as offset to allegedly imperialist-inspired
                    blockade by Kmt.</p>
                <p>In view probable Soviet inability provide more than mere driblet China’s economic
                    needs, Department may wish consider for propaganda purposes via VOA and
                    otherwise committing [<hi rend="italic">commitments?</hi>] Soviets to aid
                    program for China. It might incidentally be pointed out Soviet <hi rend="italic">quid</hi> for Chinese <hi rend="italic">quo</hi> involves such items as
                    soya beans, vegetable oil, maize and kaoliang, all of which currently in short
                    supply in Shanghai. According Communist press, Soviets will supply industrial
                    equipment, automobiles, kerosene, cloth, newsprint, pharmaceutical supplies,
                    many of which were furnished Chinese people under ECA program without exaction
                    essential goods from Chinese in return.</p>
                <p>Sent Department 3061, repeated Nanking 1695.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">McConaughy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
